   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-03-17_page01.jpg"/>
            <dateline>
               <date when="1818-03-17">Tuesday <lb/>
                  March 17.<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>1818<lb/>
               </date>
            </dateline>
            <p>
               <note>16</note>﻿
                Dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtM1">Aunt</persName> —I hope you<lb/>
                read my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtJ1">Uncle's</persName>
               <lb/>
                letter to me? I think it<lb/> 
                was one of the very best<lb/>
                playful notes I ever read<lb/>
                — It kept our little oval<lb/>
                breakfast table in a shout<lb/> 
                of applause &amp; laughter<lb/>
                as I read it—and the<lb/> 
                warm hearted praise to<lb/> 
                my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> in sober<lb/>
               <del/> earnest at the end<lb/> 
                brought tears into the<lb/>
                laughing eyes—I could not<lb/> 
                forbear sending it least<lb/>
                first to my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> —<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-03-17_page02.jpg"/>
                I know it will give her<lb/> 
                great pleasure &amp; surely<lb/>
                she deserves all we can<lb/> 
                give—We heard from<lb/> 
                her this morning (Tuesday)<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> much better<lb/>
                — <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt.<hi rend="superscript">n</hi> Beaufort</persName> will<lb/> 
                come to them immediately<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
                — <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxA1">Anne</persName> has arrived at<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Cheltenham_ENK">Cheltenham</placeName> on purpose<lb/> 
                to see them—This has<lb/> 
                given them all great<lb/>
                pleasure- The place was<lb/> 
                exceedingly dull &amp; <choice>
                  <orig>disa<lb/>
                greeable</orig>
                  <reg>disagreeable</reg>
               </choice>
                before <del>they</del> she<lb/> 
                arrived—There was only<lb/>
                a stupid old man &amp;<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-03-17_page03.jpg"/>
               <note>17</note>
                a noisy rantipole young<lb/>
                man there and a most<lb/> 
                stupid <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LoweX1">Miss Lowe</persName> —<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DandX1">M <hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Dandridge</persName>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WheeX1">M <hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Wheelers</persName>
               <lb/> 
                mother they have not<lb/> 
                yet seen— <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BoisX1">D <hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Boisogon</persName>
               <lb/> 
                very civil -&amp; a man of the<lb/> 
                world- advises <unclear>amunmen</unclear>
               <lb/>
                to W<hi rend="superscript">m</hi> eating often &amp; little at<lb/> 
                a time- little meat- no wine<lb/>
                — a warm bath at 96— &amp;<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Cheltenham_ENK">Cheltenham</placeName> waters before<lb/>
                Breakfast—pills—I know<lb/> 
                not what—<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> delighted in journey<lb/> 
                Through <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#WLK">wales</placeName> - <del>but</del>but <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName>
               <lb/> 
                Charmed with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LoweX1" cert="medium">Telford's</persName>
               <lb/>
                Works—<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
                All well here &amp; happy—<lb/> 
                — <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> gone to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Castleforbes_IE">Castle Forbes</placeName>
               <lb/>
                for two days—I am going on<lb/>
                pretty well with my work<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-03-17_page04.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName> has not the least cough<lb/>
                — is quite well &amp; I am ever<lb/> 
                yours affectionately<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria E</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <postscript>
               <p> 
                — My <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtJ1">uncle</persName> shall soon here<lb/> 
                from me- Pray desire some <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EverX1">Everard</persName>
                  <lb/>
                or other friend to call at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Merrion-Street-31_IE">31 Merrion St<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                  </placeName> for a<lb/> 
                small packet- a book for my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtJ1">uncle</persName> do not<lb/> 
                forget this- I beg—<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                        To<lb/>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtM1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Ruxton</persName>
                     <lb/>
                  </addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
